<section class="section section--alt" id="app-stack-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What an &ldquo;app stack&rdquo; actually is.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>An app stack is just the collection of software your business uses to run, connected so the pieces share data instead of being re-keyed by hand. At the center sits your accounting system &mdash; for most small businesses that&rsquo;s <code>QuickBooks</code> &mdash; and it acts as the system of record: the place where money in and money out is finally recorded. Around it you add tools for the jobs the accounting file doesn&rsquo;t do on its own: taking payments, running payroll, capturing expenses and paying bills, selling online or in person, and reporting on the result.</p>
      <p>The part people underestimate is that these aren&rsquo;t independent tools sitting side by side &mdash; they&rsquo;re plumbing. The moment you connect a payment processor, a payroll app, or an online store to your accounting file, that app starts <em>writing transactions into your books</em>. A well-designed stack means each app posts clean, predictable entries that reconcile to your bank. A bolted-on stack means two apps recording the same sale, deposits that don&rsquo;t match what hit the account, and income counted twice. The difference isn&rsquo;t the apps you pick &mdash; it&rsquo;s whether the stack was designed around the books or assembled at random.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

